SHA-256 over N pre-padded 64-byte blocks — the TLS 1.3 transcript-hash
primitive. The transcript hash is SHA-256 over the concatenated handshake
messages (variable length), so it needs a recursive fold over blocks
(like ghash_nblocks, but with the SHA-256 compression function).

sha256_fold threads the 8-word hash state through a recursive callable,
one 64-byte block per frame, terminating by `decreasing : i` over
i : number [0, 64]. The caller supplies the IV (H0 constants) as the
initial state and the message already SHA-padded to a multiple of 64
bytes, as hex (argv-safe). Each frame reads 16 big-endian words via
byte_at + hex decode, runs the 64-round compression, recurses. At i==0
returns digest byte which (0..31), big-endian from the 8 words.

Validated against hashlib/sha256sum for message lengths 0/3/11/64/100/200.
Enables Derive-Secret with a transcript context.
